# Queenswarm — Core Agent Swarm Rules

Queenswarm is a bee-hive inspired AI agent swarm for **queenswarm.love**. Apply this philosophy to **every** architectural and workflow decision.

## Philosophy

- **One agent = one bee**: a single, sharp responsibility executed extremely well.
- **Decompose work**: break large tasks into the smallest meaningful sub-workflows.
- **Local sub-swarms**: decentralized groups of roughly 5–10 agents with local “hive mind” coordination.
- **Global sync**: sync to the global hive mind about every **5 minutes** — avoid a central bottleneck.
- **Reward learning**: **pollen points** for verified outcomes; use an **Imitation Engine** so agents copy top performers.
- **Recipe Library**: persist every **verified** workflow automatically as a reusable recipe.
- **Rapid Learning Loop**: a full loop should finish in **under 60 seconds** when feasible.

## NEVER

- Monolithic agents that try to do many unrelated jobs.
- Central single-point-of-failure components (control plane, queue, or “one true” coordinator).
- Reporting results to the user **without** running applicable **simulation** / verification first.
- Hardcoded secrets — use environment variables or a secret manager, never literals in code.
- Blocking I/O or synchronous patterns where an async option exists for that stack.
- Passing routine setup to the user (commands, env keys, restarts) when you can safely run or encode it in-repo yourself.

## ALWAYS (cross-cutting)

- **Do the work here**: If the task can be finished in this environment (code edits, `.env` / config that is not secret-bearing, `docker compose`, tests, curls, restarts), **do it yourself**. Do not end with “you should run X” or offload setup to the operator unless something is **impossible without** their credentials, host-only access, or a secret you must not write to disk.
- Prefer small, composable units over “god” services or mega-prompts.
- Design for **decentralization** and periodic global sync, not permanent central choke points.
- After tasks complete, **award pollen** for verified outcomes and **save** proven flows to the **Recipe Library** when implementing that system.
- Use **structured logging** in code: include `agent_id`, `swarm_id`, and `task_id` where those concepts exist.

